1. What is JUnit and what are its features? (Detailed Answer)
What is JUnit?
JUnit is a widely used open-source testing framework for Java that helps developers perform unit testing. Unit testing means testing individual components (methods or classes) of an application to ensure they work correctly.
JUnit is mainly used in Test-Driven Development (TDD), where tests are written before writing actual code.
👉 In simple terms:
JUnit is a tool that helps verify whether Java code behaves as expected.
________________________________________
Purpose of JUnit
•	To test small units of code independently 
•	To detect bugs early in development 
•	To improve code quality 
•	To support automation of testing 
•	To ensure changes in code do not break existing functionality (regression testing) 
________________________________________
How JUnit Works
1.	Developer writes test cases using JUnit annotations 
2.	Each test method checks expected output vs actual output 
3.	JUnit runs all test cases automatically 
4.	Results are shown as PASS or FAIL 
________________________________________
Features of JUnit
1. Simple and Easy to Use
JUnit provides simple annotations like @Test, making test writing easy and readable.
________________________________________
2. Annotations Support
JUnit uses annotations to define test behavior:
•	@Test → defines test method 
•	@BeforeEach → runs before each test 
•	@AfterEach → runs after each test 
This removes the need for complex coding.
________________________________________
3. Assertions for Validation
JUnit provides assertion methods to compare expected and actual results.
Example:
assertEquals(10, 5 + 5);
If values match → test passes
If not → test fails
________________________________________
4. Test Automation
JUnit allows automatic execution of test cases without manual intervention.
This is very useful in DevOps CI/CD pipelines.
________________________________________
5. Supports Test Lifecycle Methods
JUnit provides methods to manage test execution flow:
•	Setup before tests 
•	Cleanup after tests 
This ensures proper test environment management.
________________________________________
6. Exception Testing
JUnit can test whether a method throws an expected exception.
Example:
assertThrows(ArithmeticException.class, () -> {
    int x = 10 / 0;
});
________________________________________
7. Integration with Build Tools
JUnit works with:
•	Maven 
•	Gradle 
•	Jenkins 
This makes it important in DevOps workflows.
________________________________________
8. Test Reporting
JUnit generates test reports showing:
•	Number of tests passed 
•	Number of tests failed 
•	Execution time 
________________________________________
9. Supports Test Suites
Multiple test classes can be grouped and executed together.
________________________________________
10. Continuous Integration Support
JUnit integrates with CI tools like Jenkins, helping automate testing during software development.
________________________________________
