2. What are the important annotations provided by JUnit? (Detailed Answer)
Introduction
In JUnit, annotations are special markers used to define and control the behavior of test methods and test classes. They help JUnit understand what to execute, when to execute, and how to manage tests.
JUnit annotations make testing simple, structured, and automated.
________________________________________
Important JUnit Annotations
1. @Test
•	Marks a method as a test case 
•	JUnit will execute only methods marked with @Test 
Example:
@Test
void addTest() {
    assertEquals(5, 2 + 3);
}
________________________________________
2. @BeforeEach
•	Executes before every test method 
•	Used to set up preconditions (initialize objects, variables) 
Example:
@BeforeEach
void setup() {
    System.out.println("Before each test");
}
________________________________________
3. @AfterEach
•	Executes after every test method 
•	Used for cleanup tasks (closing files, resetting data) 
________________________________________
4. @BeforeAll
•	Executes once before all test methods 
•	Must be static 
•	Used for global setup 
________________________________________
5. @AfterAll
•	Executes once after all test methods 
•	Must be static 
•	Used for global cleanup 
________________________________________
6. @Disabled
•	Used to disable a test case temporarily 
•	JUnit will skip this test 
Example:
@Disabled
@Test
void skipTest() {
    assertEquals(1, 1);
}
________________________________________
7. @DisplayName
•	Gives a custom name to test methods 
•	Improves readability of test reports 
Example:
@DisplayName("Testing Addition Functionality")
@Test
void testAdd() {
    assertEquals(10, 5 + 5);
}
________________________________________
8. @RepeatedTest
•	Repeats a test multiple times 
•	Useful for checking consistency 
Example:
@RepeatedTest(3)
void repeatTest() {
    System.out.println("Running test multiple times");
}
________________________________________
9. @Tag
•	Used to group tests (e.g., fast, slow, regression) 
•	Helpful in selective test execution 
________________________________________
10. @Nested
•	Used to create nested test classes 
•	Helps organize related tests 
________________________________________
Summary Table
Annotation	Purpose
@Test	Defines test method
@BeforeEach	Runs before each test
@AfterEach	Runs after each test
@BeforeAll	Runs once before all tests
@AfterAll	Runs once after all tests
@Disabled	Skips a test
@DisplayName	Custom test name
@RepeatedTest	Runs test multiple times
@Tag	Groups tests
@Nested	Organizes test structure
________________________________________
Conclusion
JUnit annotations are essential for structuring and controlling test execution. They simplify test automation and improve readability, making JUnit a powerful tool for unit testing in Java and DevOps pipelines.
