3. What are the JUnit assert methods? (Detailed Answer)
Introduction
In JUnit, assert methods are used to verify whether the actual output of a program matches the expected output. They are the core of unit testing because they decide whether a test case PASS or FAIL.
If an assertion fails, JUnit marks the test as failed and stops execution of that test method.
________________________________________
Purpose of Assert Methods
•	Validate program output 
•	Compare expected vs actual results 
•	Detect errors in code 
•	Ensure correctness of logic 
•	Support automated testing 
________________________________________
Important JUnit Assert Methods
1. assertEquals()
•	Checks if expected value equals actual value 
Syntax:
assertEquals(expected, actual);
Example:
assertEquals(10, 5 + 5);
________________________________________
2. assertNotEquals()
•	Checks if expected and actual values are not equal 
assertNotEquals(10, 5 + 3);
________________________________________
3. assertTrue()
•	Checks if a condition is true 
assertTrue(5 > 2);
________________________________________
4. assertFalse()
•	Checks if a condition is false 
assertFalse(5 < 2);
________________________________________
5. assertNull()
•	Checks if the object is null 
String str = null;
assertNull(str);
________________________________________
6. assertNotNull()
•	Checks if the object is not null 
String str = "Hello";
assertNotNull(str);
________________________________________
7. assertArrayEquals()
•	Compares two arrays for equality 
int[] expected = {1, 2, 3};
int[] actual = {1, 2, 3};

assertArrayEquals(expected, actual);
________________________________________
8. assertThrows() (JUnit 5)
•	Checks if a method throws a specific exception 
assertThrows(ArithmeticException.class, () -> {
    int x = 10 / 0;
});
________________________________________
9. assertSame()
•	Checks if two references point to the same object 
assertSame(obj1, obj2);
________________________________________
10. assertNotSame()
•	Checks if two references are not the same object 
assertNotSame(obj1, obj2);
________________________________________
Summary Table
Assert Method	Purpose
assertEquals	Checks equality
assertNotEquals	Checks inequality
assertTrue	Condition must be true
assertFalse	Condition must be false
assertNull	Object should be null
assertNotNull	Object should not be null
assertArrayEquals	Compares arrays
assertThrows	Checks exceptions
assertSame	Same object reference
assertNotSame	Different object reference
________________________________________
Conclusion
JUnit assert methods are essential for verifying program correctness. They help developers automatically validate expected results, making testing reliable, fast, and suitable for DevOps automation pipelines.
