4. What is the difference between JUnit 4 and JUnit 5? (Detailed Answer)
Introduction
JUnit is a widely used Java testing framework. It has evolved from JUnit 4 to JUnit 5 with major improvements in architecture, flexibility, and testing capabilities. JUnit 5 is more modern and powerful, designed to support Java 8 and above and advanced testing needs in DevOps and CI/CD pipelines.
________________________________________
JUnit 4 vs JUnit 5 Differences
1. Architecture Difference
JUnit 4
•	Single monolithic framework 
•	Everything included in one library 
•	Less flexible for extensions 
JUnit 5
•	Modular architecture 
•	Consists of 3 parts: 
o	JUnit Platform (runs tests) 
o	JUnit Jupiter (new programming model) 
o	JUnit Vintage (supports JUnit 3/4 tests) 
👉 This makes JUnit 5 more flexible and scalable.
________________________________________
2. Annotations Difference
JUnit 4	JUnit 5
@Before	@BeforeEach
@After	@AfterEach
@BeforeClass	@BeforeAll
@AfterClass	@AfterAll
@Ignore	@Disabled
👉 JUnit 5 uses more readable and consistent naming.
________________________________________
3. Java Version Support
•	JUnit 4 → Supports Java 5 and above 
•	JUnit 5 → Supports Java 8 and above (Lambda expressions supported) 
________________________________________
4. Exception Testing
JUnit 4:
@Test(expected = ArithmeticException.class)
JUnit 5:
assertThrows(ArithmeticException.class, () -> {
    int x = 10 / 0;
});
👉 JUnit 5 provides more flexible and precise exception handling
________________________________________
5. Assertions
•	JUnit 4 → Basic assertions only 
•	JUnit 5 → Advanced assertions like: 
o	assertThrows() 
o	assertAll() 
o	Lambda-based assertions 
________________________________________
6. Test Execution Model
•	JUnit 4 → No built-in support for parallel execution 
•	JUnit 5 → Supports parallel test execution, improving performance 
________________________________________
7. Extension Model
JUnit 4:
•	Uses @RunWith 
•	Limited customization 
JUnit 5:
•	Powerful extension API 
•	Easy integration with tools like: 
o	Spring Boot 
o	Mockito 
o	CI/CD pipelines 
________________________________________
8. Grouping and Tagging
•	JUnit 4 → Uses @Category 
•	JUnit 5 → Uses @Tag (simpler and more powerful) 
________________________________________
9. Test Organization
•	JUnit 4 → Less structured 
•	JUnit 5 → Supports nested tests (@Nested) for better organization 
________________________________________
10. Backward Compatibility
•	JUnit 4 tests can run in JUnit 5 using JUnit Vintage Engine 
•	JUnit 5 is fully forward-compatible for modern projects 
________________________________________
Summary Table
Feature	JUnit 4	JUnit 5
Architecture	Monolithic	Modular
Java Support	Java 5+	Java 8+
Exception Handling	Limited	Advanced
Annotations	Old naming	Improved naming
Parallel Execution	Not supported	Supported
Extension Model	Limited	Powerful
Tagging	@Category	@Tag
Test Structure	Basic	Nested tests supported
________________________________________
Conclusion
JUnit 5 is a major improvement over JUnit 4 with modular design, better annotations, advanced assertions, and strong support for modern Java features. It is highly suitable for DevOps, CI/CD pipelines, and modern software testing environments.
