5. How do you test exceptions in JUnit 5? (Detailed Answer)
Introduction
In software testing, it is important to check whether a program handles errors correctly. Sometimes, methods are expected to throw exceptions (e.g., division by zero, invalid input).
In JUnit 5, exceptions are tested using the method assertThrows(), which ensures that a specific exception is thrown during execution.
________________________________________
Testing Exceptions in JUnit 5
1. Using assertThrows()
JUnit 5 provides assertThrows() to verify exceptions.
Syntax:
assertThrows(ExceptionClass.class, () -> {
    // code that may throw exception
});
________________________________________
Example 1: ArithmeticException
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.*;

public class ExceptionTest {

    @Test
    void testDivisionByZero() {

        assertThrows(ArithmeticException.class, () -> {
            int result = 10 / 0;
        });
    }
}
Explanation:
•	The code 10 / 0 throws ArithmeticException 
•	assertThrows() verifies that this exception occurs 
•	If exception occurs → test PASS 
•	If no exception → test FAIL 
________________________________________
2. Capturing the Exception Object
We can also store and validate the exception message.
@Test
void testExceptionMessage() {

    Exception exception = assertThrows(ArithmeticException.class, () -> {
        int result = 10 / 0;
    });

    assertEquals("/ by zero", exception.getMessage());
}
________________________________________
3. Testing Custom Exceptions
If a method throws a custom exception:
class InvalidAgeException extends Exception {
    public InvalidAgeException(String message) {
        super(message);
    }
}
Test Case:
@Test
void testCustomException() {

    assertThrows(InvalidAgeException.class, () -> {
        throw new InvalidAgeException("Age not valid");
    });
}
________________________________________
4. Testing Exception in Methods
public int divide(int a, int b) {
    return a / b;
}
Test:
@Test
void testDivideMethod() {

    assertThrows(ArithmeticException.class, () -> {
        divide(10, 0);
    });
}
________________________________________
Advantages of assertThrows()
•	Simple and clean syntax 
•	Better than JUnit 4 expected parameter 
•	Allows checking exception type and message 
•	Supports lambda expressions (Java 8+) 
________________________________________
Comparison with JUnit 4
Feature	JUnit 4	JUnit 5
Exception testing	@Test(expected=Exception.class)	assertThrows()
Flexibility	Low	High
Message validation	Not possible	Possible
Lambda support	No	Yes
________________________________________
Conclusion
In JUnit 5, exceptions are tested using assertThrows(), which provides a powerful and flexible way to ensure that code handles error conditions properly. It is essential for writing robust, reliable, and production-ready software in DevOps environments.
