6. What is JaCoCo and why is it used? (Detailed Answer)
Introduction
JaCoCo (Java Code Coverage) is an open-source tool used in Java applications to measure code coverage during unit testing. It shows how much of the source code is executed when test cases run.
JaCoCo is widely used in DevOps and CI/CD pipelines to ensure that testing is effective and code quality is maintained.
________________________________________
What is Code Coverage?
Code coverage refers to the percentage of code that is executed while running test cases.
Example:
•	If a program has 100 lines of code 
•	And tests execute 80 lines
👉 Code coverage = 80% 
________________________________________
What is JaCoCo?
JaCoCo automatically:
•	Monitors test execution 
•	Records which lines of code are executed 
•	Generates detailed reports (HTML, XML, CSV) 
________________________________________
Why is JaCoCo used?
1. Measures Test Effectiveness
•	Shows how much code is tested 
•	Helps identify untested parts of the application 
________________________________________
2. Improves Code Quality
•	Encourages developers to write better test c
•	Reduces bugs in production 
________________________________________
3. Identifies Untested Code
•	Highlights missing test coverage 
•	Helps improve test completeness 
________________________________________
4. Supports CI/CD Pipeline
•	Integrated with tools like Jenkins, Maven, Gradle 
•	Automatically checks coverage during build process 
________________________________________
5. Helps in Regression Testing
•	Ensures new changes do not break existing functionality 
________________________________________
6. Provides Detailed Reports
JaCoCo generates reports in:
•	HTML (easy to view in browser) 
•	XML (used in automation tools) 
•	CSV (for analysis) 
________________________________________
Types of Coverage Provided by JaCoCo
1. Instruction Coverage
Checks whether all bytecode instructions are executed.
________________________________________
2. Line Coverage
Checks whether each line of code is executed.
________________________________________
3. Branch Coverage
Checks whether all decision branches (if-else conditions) are tested.
________________________________________
4. Method Coverage
Checks whether all methods are called during testing.
________________________________________
How JaCoCo Works (Simple Flow)
1.	Developer writes test cases using JUnit 
2.	Tests are executed 
3.	JaCoCo monitors execution 
4.	It tracks covered and uncovered code 
5.	Generates coverage report 
________________________________________
Example Use Case
If a class has an if-else condition:
•	Only if is tested → partial coverage 
•	Both if and else tested → full coverage 
JaCoCo highlights untested branch (else part)
________________________________________
Advantages of JaCoCo
•	Easy integration with Maven and Gradle 
•	Automatic reporting 
•	Improves test quality 
•	Helps maintain high code standards 
•	Essential for DevOps pipelines 
________________________________________
Conclusion
JaCoCo is a powerful Java code coverage tool used to measure how much of the code is tested. It helps developers improve test quality, find untested code, and ensure better software reliability, making it very important in DevOps and continuous integration environments.
