8. How can you improve or increase code coverage using JaCoCo? (Detailed Answer)
Introduction
Code coverage measures how much of the source code is executed when test cases run. In JaCoCo, higher coverage means more parts of the application are tested, leading to better software quality.
Improving code coverage is important in DevOps and CI/CD pipelines to ensure that every build is properly tested before deployment.
________________________________________
Ways to Improve Code Coverage Using JaCoCo
1. Write More Unit Test Cases
The most important way to increase coverage is to write additional JUnit test cases.
•	Test all methods in the class 
•	Ensure every function has at least one test 
👉 More test cases = higher coverage
________________________________________
2. Cover All Branch Conditions
Test all decision-making paths:
•	if condition 
•	else condition 
•	switch cases 
Example:
If code has:
if (age > 18) {
    System.out.println("Adult");
} else {
    System.out.println("Minor");
}
You must test:
•	age > 18 
•	age < 18 
________________________________________
3. Test Edge Cases
Edge cases are extreme inputs that often break programs.
Examples:
•	0 
•	Negative numbers 
•	Maximum values 
•	Empty strings 
👉 Testing edge cases improves coverage significantly
________________________________________
4. Use Exception Testing
Ensure all error conditions are tested using:
assertThrows(Exception.class, () -> method());
This improves branch coverage and robustness
________________________________________
5. Increase Method Coverage
Make sure:
•	Every method is called in at least one test 
•	No method is left untested 
________________________________________
6. Use Parameterized Tests
JUnit 5 allows running same test with multiple inputs:
@ParameterizedTest
@ValueSource(ints = {1, 2, 3, 4})
void testNumbers(int num) {
    assertTrue(num > 0);
}
👉 This improves coverage with less code
________________________________________
7. Refactor Untested Code
JaCoCo report shows uncovered lines.
Steps:
•	Identify red/yellow highlighted lines 
•	Write tests for them 
•	Or remove dead code 
________________________________________
8. Use CI/CD Integration
In DevOps pipelines:
•	Jenkins runs tests automatically 
•	JaCoCo generates report every build 
•	Developers fix coverage issues continuously 
________________________________________
9. Maintain High Coverage Threshold
Set minimum coverage rule (example: 80% or 90%)
If coverage is low:
•	Build fails 
•	Developers must improve tests 
________________________________________
10. Test All Classes and Layers
Ensure coverage across:
•	Controller layer 
•	Service layer 
•	Repository layer 
This is important in real-world applications.
________________________________________
Example Scenario
If a project has:
•	100 lines of code 
•	Only 60 lines executed in tests 
👉 Coverage = 60%
After improving tests:
•	90 lines executed 
👉 Coverage = 90%
________________________________________
Advantages of Improving Code Coverage
•	Detects untested code 
•	Reduces bugs in production 
•	Improves software reliability 
•	Ensures better test quality 
•	Important for DevOps automation 
________________________________________
Conclusion
Code coverage in JaCoCo can be improved by writing more unit tests, covering all branches, testing edge cases, using exception testing, and integrating tests into CI/CD pipelines. High coverage ensures better code quality and reliability in software development.
