12. What are the key components of Docker architecture? (Detailed Answer)
Introduction
Docker architecture is a client-server based system used to build, ship, and run applications inside containers. It consists of multiple components that work together to manage container lifecycle efficiently in DevOps environments.
________________________________________
Key Components of Docker Architecture
1. Docker Client
•	The Docker Client is the primary user interface to interact with Docker. 
•	Users give commands like docker run, docker build, etc. 
•	It communicates with Docker Daemon using REST API. 
Example:
docker run ubuntu
👉 Client sends request to daemon to execute the container.
________________________________________
2. Docker Daemon (dockerd)
•	The Docker Daemon is the core engine of Docker. 
•	It runs in the background on the host machine. 
•	Responsible for: 
o	Building images 
o	Running containers 
o	Managing networks and volumes 
👉 It listens for Docker API requests from the client.
________________________________________
3. Docker Images
•	A Docker Image is a read-only template used to create containers. 
•	It contains: 
o	Application code 
o	Libraries 
o	Dependencies 
o	Configuration 
👉 Images act as blueprints for containers.
________________________________________
4. Docker Containers
•	A container is a running instance of a Docker image. 
•	It is lightweight and isolated. 
•	Multiple containers can run from the same image. 
👉 Example: Running multiple web apps from same image.
________________________________________
5. Docker Registry
•	A Docker Registry is a storage system for Docker images. 
•	It can be: 
o	Public (Docker Hub) 
o	Private (company registry) 
Operations:
•	docker push → upload image 
•	docker pull → download image 
________________________________________
6. Docker Hub
•	Docker Hub is a public registry service. 
•	Used to store and share container images globally. 
•	Provides official images like: 
o	Ubuntu 
o	MySQL 
o	Node.js 
________________________________________
7. Docker Objects (Supporting Components)
a) Volumes
•	Used for data persistence 
•	Data remains even if container is deleted 
b) Networks
•	Used to connect containers 
•	Enables communication between multiple containers 
________________________________________
Docker Architecture Diagram (Flow)
User (Docker Client)
        ↓
Docker API Request
        ↓
Docker Daemon
   ↓     ↓      ↓
Images  Containers  Networks
        ↓
   Docker Registry (Docker Hub)
________________________________________
How Docker Architecture Works
1.	User runs command using Docker Client 
2.	Client sends request to Docker Daemon 
3.	Daemon checks Docker Images 
4.	Creates or runs Containers 
5.	Pulls or pushes images from/to Docker Registry 
________________________________________
Advantages of Docker Architecture
•	Lightweight and fast 
•	Efficient resource usage 
•	Easy container management 
•	Supports distributed systems 
•	Ideal for DevOps and CI/CD pipelines 
________________________________________
Conclusion
Docker architecture consists of key components like Docker Client, Docker Daemon, Images, Containers, and Registry. These components work together in a client-server model to efficiently build, manage, and deploy applications in containers, making Docker an essential tool in modern DevOps environments.
