7. How do you generate and run a JaCoCo test report? (Detailed Answer)
Introduction
JaCoCo is used in Java projects to measure code coverage. To understand how much of the code is tested, we generate a JaCoCo report after running unit tests. The report shows coverage in formats like HTML, XML, and CSV.
In real DevOps environments, this process is automated using Maven or Gradle and integrated into CI/CD tools like Jenkins.
________________________________________
How to Generate and Run JaCoCo Report (Using Maven)
Step 1: Add JaCoCo Plugin in pom.xml
First, include the JaCoCo plugin in your Maven project.
<plugin>
    <groupId>org.jacoco</groupId>
    <artifactId>jacoco-maven-plugin</artifactId>
    <version>0.8.11</version>
    <executions>
        <execution>
            <goals>
                <goal>prepare-agent</goal>
            </goals>
        </execution>

        <execution>
            <id>report</id>
            <phase>test</phase>
            <goals>
                <goal>report</goal>
            </goals>
        </execution>
    </executions>
</plugin>
________________________________________
Step 2: Write JUnit Test Cases
Example:
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.*;

public class CalculatorTest {

    @Test
    void testAdd() {
        assertEquals(10, 5 + 5);
    }
}
________________________________________
Step 3: Run Tests Using Maven
Execute the following command:
mvn clean test
What happens here:
•	Project is cleaned 
•	Test cases are executed using JUnit 
•	JaCoCo collects coverage data 
________________________________________
Step 4: Generate JaCoCo Report
Run:
mvn jacoco:report
________________________________________
Step 5: View the Report
After execution, report is generated at:
target/site/jacoco/index.html
Open this file in browser to view:
•	Line coverage 
•	Branch coverage 
•	Method coverage 
•	Missed lines of code 
________________________________________
Working Flow of JaCoCo Report Generation
1.	Write Java code 
2.	Write JUnit test cases 
3.	Run mvn test 
4.	JaCoCo collects execution data 
5.	Run mvn jacoco:report 
6.	HTML report is generated 
________________________________________
Types of Reports Generated
1. HTML Report
•	Easy to read in browser 
•	Shows color-coded coverage 
________________________________________
2. XML Report
•	Used in CI/CD tools like Jenkins 
•	Machine-readable 
________________________________________
3. CSV Report
•	Used for data analysis 
________________________________________
Integration with CI/CD (Important Point)
In DevOps pipelines:
•	Jenkins automatically runs mvn test 
•	JaCoCo generates coverage report 
•	Reports are published after every build 
________________________________________
Advantages
•	Automatic report generation 
•	Helps track code quality 
•	Easy integration with Maven 
•	Useful for DevOps automation 
•	Identifies untested code areas 
________________________________________
Conclusion
To generate a JaCoCo report, we add the plugin in Maven, run unit tests using mvn test, and then generate the report using mvn jacoco:report. The final HTML report shows detailed code coverage, helping developers improve test quality and ensuring better software reliability in DevOps pipelines.
