14. How do you start, stop, and kill a Docker container? (Detailed Answer)
Introduction
In Docker, containers can be controlled using different commands such as start, stop, and kill. These commands are used to manage the lifecycle of containers in DevOps environments, especially during development, testing, and deployment.
________________________________________
1. Starting a Docker Container
Meaning
The start command is used to run a container that is already created but currently in a stopped state.
Command:
docker start container_id
Explanation:
•	It starts an existing container 
•	The container resumes execution from where it stopped 
•	It does NOT create a new container 
________________________________________
Example:
docker start my_container
________________________________________
2. Stopping a Docker Container
Meaning
The stop command is used to gracefully stop a running container.
Command:
docker stop container_id
Explanation:
•	Sends a SIGTERM signal (graceful shutdown) 
•	Gives time for processes to exit safely 
•	Preserves container state 
•	Can be restarted later 
________________________________________
Example:
docker stop my_container
________________________________________
3. Killing a Docker Container
Meaning
The kill command is used to forcefully stop a running container.
Command:
docker kill container_id
Explanation:
•	Sends a SIGKILL signal 
•	Immediately stops the container 
•	No time for cleanup or saving state 
•	Used when container is unresponsive 
________________________________________
Example:
docker kill my_container
________________________________________
Difference Between Stop and Kill
Feature	Stop	Kill
Type	Graceful shutdown	Forceful shutdown
Signal	SIGTERM	SIGKILL
Cleanup	Allowed	Not allowed
Time	Takes few seconds	Immediate
Use case	Normal shutdown	Emergency stop
________________________________________
Docker Container Flow
Created → Started → Running → (Stop / Kill) → Restart or Remove
________________________________________
Important Notes
•	start is used for stopped containers 
•	stop is safe and recommended 
•	kill is used only in emergency situations 
•	These commands do NOT delete containers 
________________________________________
Conclusion
Docker provides start, stop, and kill commands to control container execution. The start command runs a stopped container, stop gracefully shuts it down, and kill forcefully terminates it. These commands are essential for managing containers efficiently in DevOps workflows.
