17. What is virtualization, and what are the key components of a virtualization stack? (Detailed Answer)
________________________________________
Introduction
Virtualization is a technology that allows multiple virtual systems (called Virtual Machines – VMs) to run on a single physical machine. Each virtual machine behaves like an independent computer with its own operating system and applications.
👉 In simple terms:
Virtualization means creating multiple virtual computers inside one physical computer.
________________________________________
What is Virtualization?
Virtualization is the process of creating a virtual version of hardware resources, such as:
•	CPU 
•	Memory (RAM) 
•	Storage 
•	Network 
This is done using a special software layer called a Hypervisor.
________________________________________
Example
A single physical server can run:
•	Windows VM 
•	Linux VM 
•	Ubuntu VM 
All at the same time, independently.
________________________________________
Key Benefits of Virtualization
•	Better resource utilization 
•	Cost reduction (less hardware needed) 
•	Isolation between systems 
•	Easy backup and recovery 
•	Supports cloud computing 
________________________________________
Key Components of Virtualization Stack
A virtualization stack is the layered architecture that enables virtualization.
________________________________________
1. Physical Hardware Layer
This is the actual machine.
Includes:
•	CPU 
•	RAM 
•	Hard disk / SSD 
•	Network devices 
👉 It provides the base resources for virtualization.
________________________________________
2. Host Operating System (Optional in Type 2)
•	Installed directly on physical hardware 
•	Manages hardware resources 
👉 Example: Windows, Linux
________________________________________
3. Hypervisor (Most Important Component)
A Hypervisor is the software layer that creates and manages virtual machines.
Types of Hypervisors:
Type 1 (Bare Metal)
•	Runs directly on hardware 
•	Faster and more efficient 
